      "result": "\u003coutput\u003e\n{\n  \"rating\": 2,\n  \"summary\": \"The #614 test file covers the happy-path multi-provider scenarios well but has two blocking gaps: (1) no lockstep test comparing legacy and canonical template families against the same inputs, which AGENTS.md explicitly mandates, and (2) the canonical render path for a bedrock auxiliary provider is entirely untested — _build_provider_env_views has bedrock-aux branching with no canonical render_hermes test exercising it. Several additional warning-level gaps exist around the canonical env single-provider back-compat path, multi-aux-role coverage, and role collision behavior.\",\n  \"findings\": [\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"blocking\",\n      \"location\": \"tests/test_hermes_multi_provider_templates.py (missing test)\",\n      \"issue\": \"No lockstep test asserting legacy (hermes.env.j2 / hermes-config.yaml.j2) and canonical (hermes-env.canonical.j2 / hermes-config.canonical.yaml.j2) produce structurally identical output for the same logical configuration. AGENTS.md §'Template lockstep' explicitly requires this until the two-family consolidation lands. Without it, a field landing in only one family silently diverges — exactly the class of bug the rule was written to prevent. There is no test feeding the multi-provider conflict scenario, the explicit-title_generation shadow scenario, or the multiple-aux-roles scenario through both families and asserting parity.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Add a parametrized lockstep class that feeds the same logical inputs to both families for at least: (a) single-provider anthropic, (b) multi-provider same-type conflict (WARNING path), (c) explicit title_generation attachment, (d) multiple different-type auxiliaries. Assert `yaml.safe_load(legacy_yaml) == yaml.safe_load(canonical_yaml)` for config and that the set of emitted env-var names matches between legacy_env and canonical_env.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"blocking\",\n      \"location\": 