      "result": "\u003coutput\u003e\n{\n  \"rating\": 2,\n  \"summary\": \"#614 adds structurally correct auxiliary: block logic to both config templates and correct dedup logic to both env templates, with consistent filter usage (yaml_quote/yq for YAML, shell_quote/shq for env). However the entire multi-provider code path (AuxiliaryProviderInputs, _build_provider_env_views, aux YAML block with actual aux providers, conflict detection, explicit-title_gen suppression) has zero test coverage — all byte-locks cover only the single-provider default-title_gen case. One state-machine gap in the legacy env template bedrock dedup, model map triplication, and an ordering lockstep divergence compound the picture.\",\n  \"findings\": [\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"blocking\",\n      \"location\": \"tests/core/test_render.py (absent)\",\n      \"issue\": \"Zero test coverage for the core #614 code paths. AuxiliaryProviderInputs is never imported in test_render.py; auxiliary_providers is never set to anything other than the empty-tuple default in any RenderInputs fixture. _build_provider_env_views (conflict detection, same-type dedup), _build_aux_yaml_views (aux YAML block), explicit title_gen suppression, and multi-provider env conflict WARNING emission are all untested. The byte-lock discipline established by the prior ATX rounds covers only the single-provider title_generation DEFAULT path. The #614 acceptance criterion — 'same-type-different-key surfaces a WARNING comment', 'explicit title_generation attachment suppresses the per-primary-type default', 'Bedrock AWS triplet emitted once' across primary+aux — has no regression lock.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Add byte-lock tests covering at minimum: (a) two non-conflicting aux providers (different types) → correct auxiliary: block order + both API keys in .env; (b) same-type conflict (e.g., two openrouter attachments with different keys) → WARNING comment emitted in both legacy and canonical env; (c) explicit title_generation aux → default title_generation NOT emitted in config.yaml; (d) Bedrock primary + Bedrock aux with same credentials → one AWS triplet, no conflict; (e) Bedrock primary + Bedrock aux with different credentials → conflict WARNING. Mirror each byte-lock against the canonical (render_hermes) path at minimum.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"warning\",\n      \"location\": \"src/clawrium/platform/registry/hermes/templates/hermes-config.yaml.j2:32 vs hermes-config.canonical.yaml.j2:59-76 + render.py:451\",\n      \"issue\": \"Auxiliary YAML key ORDER diverges between the two templates. Canonical template receives aux_providers sorted alphabetically by role (render.py:451: auxiliary_provider_inputs.sort(key=lambda p: p.role)), so a vision+title_generation pair renders title_generation first. Legacy template iterates _explicit_aux.items() in insertion order (first seen in config.providers), so the same pair renders in attachment order. For a single aux provider there is no visible difference. For 2+ aux providers, a clawctl agent configure (Ansible path) followed by clawctl agent sync (canonical path) produces different bytes on disk. AGENTS.md says 'both templates must render the same auxiliary: shape'; the project's own byte-lock discipline would flag this on any multi-aux test case.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Align the ordering: either sort _explicit_aux by role in the legacy template ({% for _role, _entry in _explicit_aux.items() | sort(attribute=0) %}) or drop the sort at render.py:451 and accept insertion order in both paths. Alphabetical sort in the canonical path is safer (deterministic regardless of API call order); mirror it in the legacy template to close the lockstep gap.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"warning\",\n      \"location\": \"render.py:744-749 + hermes-config.yaml.j2:37-42 + hermes-config.canonical.yaml.j2:13-18\",\n      \"issue\": \"_default_title_gen_map / _HERMES_DEFAULT_TITLE_GEN_MODEL is defined in three independent places. The Python constant at render.py:744-749 is never passed to any template (neither yaml_body nor env_body context in render_hermes includes it). Both Jinja templates define their own inline copy. Any model bump (e.g., haiku model ID change) requires 3 simultaneous edits; the Python constant will silently drift from the templates' in-use values and create a false impression of a single source of truth.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Thread _HERMES_DEFAULT_TITLE_GEN_MODEL through to both templates via the render context (yaml_body kwargs: default_title_gen_map=_HERMES_DEFAULT_TITLE_GEN_MODEL) and remove the inline definition from both .j2 files. Until the two-template-family consolidation lands, at minimum remove the dead Python constant or add a comment that it is documentation-only and must be kept in sync manually with the template inline dicts.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"warning\",\n      \"location\": \"src/clawrium/platform/registry/hermes/templates/hermes.env.j2:47-58\",\n      \"issue\": \"Legacy env template bedrock dedup has a state-machine gap: _seen_type_keys is only updated when both _aws.get('access_key') and _aws.get('secret_key') are truthy (lines 48-49). If the first bedrock provider in config.providers has empty credentials (emission skipped), _seen_type_keys is NOT updated. A second same-type bedrock provider with real credentials then passes the 'not in _seen_type_keys' guard and emits its own AWS triplet without any conflict check — the primary intent of the dedup is bypassed. The canonical Python path (_build_provider_env_views, render.py:779-788) always calls _add_view for bedrock regardless of credential emptiness, so seen_type_keys is always marked. The build_render_inputs assembler prevents empty bedrock creds on the canonical path, but the Ansible path uses the legacy template directly and does not share that guard.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Move the seen_type_keys update unconditionally before the credential emission guard: set the key to the computed _key_compare regardless of whether credentials are present. Empty credentials produce a degenerate key ('|') that will match a second empty-credentials bedrock (drop) or conflict with a non-empty one (WARNING) — both behaviors are correct.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"warning\",\n      \"location\": \"hermes-config.yaml.j2:135 + hermes-config.canonical.yaml.j2:69 (auxiliary ollama branch)\",\n      \"issue\": \"Both templates emit provider: \\\"custom\\\" for an ollama auxiliary slot with no base_url field. The primary-model ollama path correctly emits base_url (hermes-config.yaml.j2:94-97, hermes-config.canonical.yaml.j2:45). If upstream NousResearch/hermes-agent hermes_cli/config.py:716-795 supports base_url in auxiliary.\u003crole\u003e: mappings, any ollama-as-aux attachment silently produces a broken auxiliary config (hermes validates lazily — no error until first aux request). If the upstream schema only accepts {provider, model} in aux slots (per the AGENTS.md comment), ollama-as-aux is architecturally unsupported but the data layer doesn't block it: ollama is in _AGENT_TYPE_PROVIDER_SUPPORT['hermes'] and AUXILIARY_SLOTS imposes no provider-type restriction.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Verify NousResearch/hermes-agent hermes_cli/config.py:716-795 for whether base_url is a valid field in auxiliary.\u003crole\u003e: mappings. If it is, add base_url emission for ollama-type aux entries (both templates). If it isn't, add an AttachmentError in build_render_inputs when aux_type == 'ollama' (ollama as auxiliary is non-functional regardless of what we emit). Either way, add a test.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"warning\",\n      \"location\": \"hermes-config.yaml.j2:37-42 + hermes-config.canonical.yaml.j2:13-18 (single-provider back-compat)\",\n      \"issue\": \"Post-#614, every non-ollama hermes agent acquires a new auxiliary: title_generation: model: ... section in config.yaml on next configure or sync. Pre-#614 no auxiliary